# AgentOps Setup Guide
[(back to main README)](../README.md)

## Overview

This guide walks you through setting up your AgentOps project from init to production deployment. By the end you'll have CI/CD deploying your agent as a Databricks App across staging and production workspaces.

## Prerequisites

- [Databricks CLI](https://docs.databricks.com/en/dev-tools/cli/install.html) v0.288.0+
- [uv](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/getting-started/installation/) package manager
- Python 3.11+
- A Databricks workspace with Unity Catalog enabled
- Account admin access (for service principals)
- Workspace admin access in staging and prod workspaces

## Step 1: Initialize the project

If you haven't already:

```bash
databricks bundle init https://github.com/sdonohoo-db/agentops-stacks
```

This asks 5 questions (project name, cloud, CI/CD platform, setup scope) and generates the project scaffold.

## Step 2: Install your agent framework

```bash
cd {{ .input_root_dir }}
uv run setup
```

The setup script queries GitHub for available agent templates from [databricks/app-templates](https://github.com/databricks/app-templates) and presents a numbered menu. Pick a framework (LangGraph, OpenAI Agents SDK, multi-agent, etc.) and the script installs the agent code into your project.

If you're on an air-gapped network, the script provides a manual download URL as fallback.

### Available templates and required resources

The setup script presents all available options grouped by category. Some templates depend on Databricks resources that must exist before you deploy — create these in your workspace first.

#### Build Agent

| Template | Required Resources |
|---|---|
| Empty Agent Scaffold | _(none)_ |
| Create DAB from existing solution (Future) | — |

#### Agent App Example Templates

| Template | Required Resources |
|---|---|
| `agent-langgraph` | _(none)_ |
| `agent-openai-agents-sdk` | _(none)_ |
| `agent-openai-agents-sdk-multiagent` | _(none)_ |
| `agent-migration-from-model-serving` | _(none)_ |
| `agent-non-conversational` | _(none)_ |
| `agent-langgraph-long-term-memory` | Lakebase (PostgreSQL) |
| `agent-langgraph-short-term-memory` | Lakebase (PostgreSQL) |
| `agent-openai-agents-sdk-short-term-memory` | Lakebase (PostgreSQL) |
| `agent-openai-agents-sdk-long-running-agent` | Lakebase (PostgreSQL) |
| `mcp-server-hello-world` | _(none)_ |
| `mcp-server-open-api-spec` | UC Connection, UC Volume |

#### Solution patterns (Future)

| Template | Required Resources |
|---|---|
| RAG agent | Vector Search index, UC Volume |
| Document Intelligence agent | UC Volume |
| RPA / Process Automation agent | Lakebase, external API connections |

**Empty agent** generates a minimal working agent locally with no framework dependency beyond MLflow and FastAPI. It includes the standard scaffolding (`start_server.py`, `utils.py`, `app.yaml`, evaluation, preflight checks) with a placeholder `agent.py` that implements the `@invoke()` / `@stream()` contract and a single example tool. You fill in your own agent logic — useful when none of the framework templates fit or you want to start from scratch.

**Capture existing agent** will reverse-engineer a running Databricks App into a DAB project. This is planned for a future release.

### Lakebase (Autoscaling PostgreSQL)

Required by the 4 memory-enabled templates. Create an autoscaling Lakebase project and branch in your workspace before deploying.

1. Create a Lakebase project: Workspace sidebar > Lakebase > New Project (select "Autoscaling")
2. Create a branch within the project
3. Note the project name and branch name

Configure in your project's `app.yaml` (env section) or `.env` for local dev:
```
LAKEBASE_AUTOSCALING_PROJECT=your-project-name
LAKEBASE_AUTOSCALING_BRANCH=your-branch-name
```

See [Lakebase documentation](https://docs.databricks.com/en/lakebase/index.html).

### Serving Endpoint

Optional for `agent-openai-agents-sdk-multiagent`, required for `agent-langchain-ts`. Create or identify a model serving endpoint in your workspace.

Configure in `app.yaml` or `.env`:
```
DATABRICKS_SERVING_ENDPOINT=databricks-claude-sonnet-4-5
```

### UC Connection + UC Volume

Required by `mcp-server-open-api-spec`. Create a Unity Catalog connection to the external API and upload the OpenAPI spec file to a UC Volume.

1. Create a UC Connection: Catalog Explorer > External Data > Connections > Create Connection
2. Create a UC Volume: Catalog Explorer > select catalog/schema > Create Volume
3. Upload the OpenAPI spec file to the volume

Configure in `app.yaml` or `.env`:
```
UC_CONNECTION_NAME=your-connection-name
UC_VOLUME_PATH=/Volumes/catalog/schema/volume/spec.yaml
```

## Step 3: Create a Git repo

Initialize Git and push to your hosted repo:

```bash
git init --initial-branch=main
git remote add upstream <your-repo-url>
```

{{- if (eq .input_setup_cicd_and_project `CICD_and_Project`)}}

Push the initial project structure:

```bash
git add README.md docs .gitignore resources/README_agentops.md
git commit -m "Add project README"
git push upstream main
```
{{ else }}

Push the CI/CD scaffolding:

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Add CI/CD scaffolding"
git push upstream main
```
{{ end }}

## Step 4: Configure workspace targets

Edit `databricks.yml` and set the `host:` URL for each target. You can use [CLI profiles](https://docs.databricks.com/en/dev-tools/cli/profiles.html) instead of hardcoding hosts:

```yaml
targets:
  dev:
    workspace:
      host: https://<your-dev-workspace-url>
```

Set Unity Catalog `uc_catalog` and `schema` values under each target's variables section if the defaults don't match your workspace.

