## Step 5: Configure CI/CD — GitHub Actions

### Create service principals

Create two service principals — one for staging deployments, one for production. Add each to the corresponding workspace.

{{ if eq .input_cloud `azure` -}}
Follow [Add a service principal to your Azure Databricks account]({{ template `generate_doc_link` (map (pair "cloud" .input_cloud) (pair "path" "administration-guide/users-groups/service-principals#--add-a-service-principal-to-your-azure-databricks-account")) }}).

### Set GitHub secrets

Get your service principal credentials (tenant ID, application ID, client secret) for both staging and prod, then add these as [encrypted secrets](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/security-guides/encrypted-secrets) in your GitHub repo:

- `STAGING_AZURE_SP_TENANT_ID`
- `STAGING_AZURE_SP_APPLICATION_ID`
- `STAGING_AZURE_SP_CLIENT_SECRET`
- `PROD_AZURE_SP_TENANT_ID`
- `PROD_AZURE_SP_APPLICATION_ID`
- `PROD_AZURE_SP_CLIENT_SECRET`
- `WORKFLOW_TOKEN` — a [GitHub PAT](https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/managing-your-personal-access-tokens#creating-a-personal-access-token-classic) with workflow permissions
{{ else -}}
Follow [Add a service principal to your Databricks account]({{ template `generate_doc_link` (map (pair "cloud" .input_cloud) (pair "path" "administration-guide/users-groups/service-principals.html#add-a-service-principal-to-your-databricks-account")) }}).

### Set GitHub secrets

Get service principal tokens for staging and prod, then add these as [encrypted secrets](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/security-guides/encrypted-secrets) in your GitHub repo:

- `STAGING_WORKSPACE_TOKEN` — service principal token for staging
- `PROD_WORKSPACE_TOKEN` — service principal token for prod
- `WORKFLOW_TOKEN` — a [GitHub PAT](https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/managing-your-personal-access-tokens#creating-a-personal-access-token-classic) with workflow permissions
{{ end }}
Update [Workflow Permissions](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/security-guides/automatic-token-authentication#modifying-the-permissions-for-the-github_token) under Repo Settings > Actions > General:
- Enable "Read and write permissions"
- Allow workflows to open pull requests

### Set up the CI/CD pipeline

Run the [Deploy CICD workflow](../.github/workflows/deploy-cicd.yml) manually from the GitHub Actions UI with `project_name` as the parameter. This generates project-specific workflow files under `.github/workflows/`.

{{ else if (eq .input_cicd_platform `azure_devops`) -}}
## Step 5: Configure CI/CD — Azure DevOps

### Create service principals

Create two service principals — one for staging, one for production. Add each to the corresponding workspace.

{{ if (eq .input_cloud `azure`) -}}
Follow [Add a service principal to your Azure Databricks account]({{ template `generate_doc_link` (map (pair "cloud" .input_cloud) (pair "path" "administration-guide/users-groups/service-principals#--add-a-service-principal-to-your-azure-databricks-account")) }}).
{{ else -}}
Follow [Add a service principal to your Databricks account]({{ template `generate_doc_link` (map (pair "cloud" .input_cloud) (pair "path" "administration-guide/users-groups/service-principals.html#add-a-service-principal-to-your-databricks-account")) }}).
{{ end }}

### Commit pipeline files

```bash
git add .azure
git commit -m "Add Azure DevOps pipeline files"
git push upstream main
```

### Create pipelines and variable group

1. Create Azure Pipelines for each YAML file under `.azure/devops-pipelines/` using the "Existing Azure Pipelines YAML file" option. See [Create your first pipeline](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/devops/pipelines/create-first-pipeline).

2. Create a variable group called `{{ .input_root_dir }} variable group` with these secrets:
{{ if (eq .input_cloud `azure`) }}
   - `STAGING_AZURE_SP_TENANT_ID`, `STAGING_AZURE_SP_APPLICATION_ID`, `STAGING_AZURE_SP_CLIENT_SECRET`
   - `PROD_AZURE_SP_TENANT_ID`, `PROD_AZURE_SP_APPLICATION_ID`, `PROD_AZURE_SP_CLIENT_SECRET`
{{ else }}
   - `STAGING_WORKSPACE_TOKEN` — service principal token for staging
   - `PROD_WORKSPACE_TOKEN` — service principal token for prod
{{ end }}
   See [Create a variable group](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/devops/pipelines/library/variable-groups?view=azure-devops&tabs=classic#create-a-variable-group).

3. Grant the pipelines access to the variable group under "Pipeline permissions."

4. Set [build validation branch policies](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/devops/repos/git/branch-policies?view=azure-devops&tabs=browser#build-validation) for the `main` branch. For monorepos, add a [path filter](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/devops/repos/git/branch-policies?view=azure-devops&tabs=browser#path-filters) so pipelines only trigger on changes to this project's directory.

### Pipeline permissions

The deploy-cicd pipeline's Build Service needs these permissions (Project Settings > Repositories > Security):
- Contribute
- Create Branch
- Contribute to pull requests

{{ else if (eq .input_cicd_platform `gitlab`) -}}
## Step 5: Configure CI/CD — GitLab Pipelines

### Create service principals

Create service principals for staging and production. Add each to the corresponding workspace.

Follow [Add a service principal to your Databricks account]({{ template `generate_doc_link` (map (pair "cloud" .input_cloud) (pair "path" "administration-guide/users-groups/service-principals.html#add-a-service-principal-to-your-databricks-account")) }}).

### Configure GitLab environments and secrets

1. Set up [GitLab environments](https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/ci/environments/): `integration`, `stage`, `production`.

2. Add [CI/CD variables](https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/ci/variables/) scoped to each environment:
   - `SP_CLIENT_ID` — service principal client ID
   - `SP_CLIENT_SECRET` — service principal client secret (masked and hidden)

### Set the pipeline configuration path

Go to Settings > CI/CD > General Pipelines > CI/CD configuration file, and set it to:

```
.gitlab/pipelines/{{ .input_project_name }}-triggers-cicd.yml
```

### Docker image

Pipelines use `databricksfieldeng/mlopsstacks:latest` by default. To customize, build from `.gitlab/docker/` and update the `image:` line in each pipeline YAML file under `.gitlab/pipelines/`.

{{ end }}

### Service principal permissions

Each service principal needs these Unity Catalog permissions in its target workspace:
- `USE_CATALOG`
- `USE_SCHEMA`
- `MODIFY`
- `CREATE_MODEL`
- `CREATE_TABLE`
- `CREATE_VOLUME`

{{- if (eq .input_setup_cicd_and_project `CICD_and_Project`)}}

## Step 6: Merge initial agent code

Create a PR with your agent code:

```bash
git checkout -b add-agent-code
git add .
git commit -m "Add agent code"
git push upstream add-agent-code
```

Open a PR to `main`. CI validates the bundle and runs tests. After review and merge, pull the changes:

```bash
git checkout main
git pull upstream main
```

## Step 7: Create the release branch

```bash
git checkout -b release main
git push upstream release
git checkout main
```

Staging deploys from `main`. Production deploys from `release`. Promote code to production by merging `main` into `release`.

## Step 8: Deploy resources

Follow [resources/README_agentops.md](../resources/README_agentops.md) for deploying agent resources and enabling production jobs.
{{- end }}

## Troubleshooting

**Bundle validation fails**: Run `databricks bundle validate -t dev` and check for missing variable values or workspace connectivity issues. Make sure your CLI profile or token is configured.

**Agent not configured**: If you see `NotImplementedError: Agent not configured`, run `uv run setup` to install an agent framework.

**App doesn't start after deploy**: Bundle deploy creates the app but doesn't start it. Start manually with `databricks apps start <app-name>` or from the workspace UI.

**Setup script can't reach GitHub**: If you're behind a firewall, the setup script prints a manual download URL. Clone the [app-templates repo](https://github.com/databricks/app-templates) and copy the template directory contents into your project.
